1
00:00:06,155 --> 00:00:08,392
Let's talk about
the International Space Station,

2
00:00:08,392 --> 00:00:13,690
the agreements about
the collaboration of several nations,

3
00:00:13,690 --> 00:00:16,367
on the program
of the International Space Station

4
00:00:16,367 --> 00:00:19,121
was signed at the beginning of 1998

5
00:00:19,121 --> 00:00:23,904
between the United States,
Russia, Canada, Japan,

6
00:00:23,904 --> 00:00:25,603
and the European Space Agency,

7
00:00:25,603 --> 00:00:29,596
representing the 11 member states of ESA
that contributed to the project,

8
00:00:29,596 --> 00:00:32,828
so 15 contributing nations total.

9
00:00:33,021 --> 00:00:37,216
The idea was really to make available
to all these partners

10
00:00:37,216 --> 00:00:42,084
a world-class laboratory in space
for life science, materials science,

11
00:00:42,084 --> 00:00:45,782
Earth observations, solar physics,
and also technology development,

12
00:00:45,782 --> 00:00:50,436
and mainly the development
of techniques and support

13
00:00:50,436 --> 00:00:54,179
of long-duration space flight
in the Solar System in the future.

14
00:00:54,946 --> 00:00:57,041
You see the flags
of all the nations involved,

15
00:00:57,041 --> 00:01:01,036
and on the upper-right side,
you see the planned architecture

16
00:01:01,036 --> 00:01:04,682
of the International Space Station,
a very successful program.

17
00:01:05,566 --> 00:01:09,087
In this special video
we talked already about mating

18
00:01:09,087 --> 00:01:12,328
of the first two elements of the Station,

19
00:01:12,328 --> 00:01:16,600
which were the Zarya Russian module

20
00:01:16,600 --> 00:01:19,263
together with the Unity node, the Node 1,

21
00:01:19,263 --> 00:01:21,707
which was the first American element,

22
00:01:21,707 --> 00:01:27,115
and sometime later,
another module, a Russian module,

23
00:01:27,115 --> 00:01:31,703
the service module Zvezda was added.

24
00:01:31,703 --> 00:01:36,018
About two years after the beginning
of the assembly of the Station,

25
00:01:36,018 --> 00:01:39,697
we had the arrival of the first crew,
and you see here the Soyuz,

26
00:01:39,697 --> 00:01:44,308
which allowed three crew members
to come as the first crew of ISS,

27
00:01:44,308 --> 00:01:49,203
which has been permanently inhabited
from that time on until now.

28
00:01:50,300 --> 00:01:54,582
These are the first
brave crew members of ISS:

29
00:01:55,033 --> 00:01:58,444
Sergei Krikalev, from Russia, is here;

30
00:01:58,444 --> 00:02:01,303
Bill Shepherd, and Yuri Gidzenko.

31
00:02:01,303 --> 00:02:03,431
So they were the first occupants of ISS,

32
00:02:03,431 --> 00:02:05,525
and they stayed
for several months on board.

33
00:02:05,710 --> 00:02:08,946
The Space Station assembly continued,

34
00:02:10,326 --> 00:02:12,346
mainly with the arrival
of the Space Shuttle,

35
00:02:12,346 --> 00:02:16,254
which was bringing crew members
and new elements for the Station.

36
00:02:16,254 --> 00:02:20,344
This is the arrival
of the Unity airlock, US airlock.

37
00:02:20,344 --> 00:02:24,413
It was allowing, from that time on,
to perform space walks

38
00:02:24,413 --> 00:02:26,756
in support of the Space Station assembly

39
00:02:26,756 --> 00:02:29,880
from the Unity airlock,
and not from the Shuttle airlock.

40
00:02:29,880 --> 00:02:32,705
Well, little by little,
the Station was being assembled.

41
00:02:32,705 --> 00:02:36,951
Here we see the arrival
of the first US solar panels, on top.

42
00:02:36,951 --> 00:02:38,300
These are the large solar panels

43
00:02:38,300 --> 00:02:42,941
that eventually were going
to be four in number,

44
00:02:42,941 --> 00:02:47,689
and at the end of the large side truss
that will be installed later.

45
00:02:47,689 --> 00:02:50,986
But at that time,
we needed already extra power,

46
00:02:50,986 --> 00:02:53,587
and the power generated
by the solar panels

47
00:02:53,587 --> 00:02:56,127
on the two Russian modules
was not enough,

48
00:02:56,127 --> 00:02:59,842
so there were added solar panels
from the US side.

49
00:03:00,098 --> 00:03:03,062
One big challenge, from the construction
and assembly point of view,

50
00:03:03,062 --> 00:03:07,813
was the assembly
of the large truss, the side truss,

51
00:03:07,813 --> 00:03:13,517
along the <i>+Y / -Y</i>
body direction of the Station,

52
00:03:13,946 --> 00:03:17,473
at the end of which were going
to be installed the large solar panels.

53
00:03:17,473 --> 00:03:21,294
And here we see the installation
of one truss segment,

54
00:03:21,294 --> 00:03:24,605
the end truss segment
on the port side, and solar arrays.

55
00:03:25,109 --> 00:03:29,707
And in the background, by the way,
you see the Greek islands,

56
00:03:29,707 --> 00:03:32,599
